Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — simple string parameter:**
```csharp
// From ProductListPage or its ViewModel
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**3. Navigate — passing the full object:**
```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
}
```

**4. Receive both on the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // Load product from a service using productId
        }

        // Approach 2: full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var productObj) 
            && productObj is Product product)
        {
            // Use product directly — no extra lookup needed
            Name = product.Name;
            Price = product.Price;
        }
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | Query string (`?key=val`) | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Arrives as** | `string` in the dictionary | Original CLR object |
| **Use when** | Deep links, simple IDs | In-app nav with rich data |

> **Tip:** The `Dictionary<string, object>` overload (approach 2) only works for in-app navigation — it can't be triggered from a URI deep link. Use string parameters when you need deep-link support.
